This guide outlines a few ways to interact with Microsoft Access, SQL Server, and ESRI Geodatabases from R.

Load the dplyr package because it is awesome - see last months presentation by Derek Sonderegger. (However, it isn’t necessary for interacting with DBs)

library(dplyr)

1 RODBC Package

The RODBC package provides the tools to interact with data in databases using an ODBC connection. ODBC provides an open, vendor- neutral way of accessing data stored in a variety of proprietary databases.

Install RODBC package if you haven’t previously.

install.packages("RODBC")

Load the RODBC package.

library(RODBC)

NOTE: For RODBC to work, both R and the database need to be using the same bit version (32-bit, 64-bit)(i.e. if you are running 32-bit Access, you need to use 32-bit R). You can change which version of R you are running by going to Tools > Global Options…

2 Databases

In order to use a database, we need to form a connection. This tells R the type of database and how to interact with this database.

View available ODBC data sources.

odbcDataSources()

3 Access

Set the database location.

accessdb <- "C:\\NAZRUG\\MikeGarage.accdb"

3.6 Use a SQL query to retrieve data across multiple tables

Using sqlQuery().

accesscon <- odbcConnectAccess2007(accessdb)
  customervehicles <- sqlQuery(accesscon, "SELECT Customers.[First Name], Customers.[Last Name], 
                              Vehicles.Make, Vehicles.Model FROM Customers INNER JOIN Vehicles ON 
                              Customers.ID = Vehicles.Owner;")
close(accesscon)

customervehicles
##   First Name Last Name     Make      Model
## 1      Marty      Last    Dodge    Caravan
## 2      Sally     First Mercedes       G500
## 3      Sally     First     Ford Mustang GT

3.7 Creating a new table

Using sqlSave().

#create a new data frame
hotrod = data.frame(Type = "Pickup", SubType = "Stepside", Year = 1969, Make = "Chevy", Model = "C/K 10", Color = "Yellow")

accesscon <- odbcConnectAccess2007(accessdb)
  sqlSave(accesscon, hotrod, tablename = "Hotrod", append = F, rownames = "ID", addPK = T)
close(accesscon)

3.8 Append data to an existing table

Using sqlSave().

#create a new data frame
hotrod = data.frame(ID = 2, Type = "Car", SubType = NA, Year = 1974, Make = "Plymouth", Model = "Gold Duster", Color = "Cream")

accesscon <- odbcConnectAccess2007(accessdb)
 sqlSave(accesscon, hotrod, tablename = "Hotrod", append = TRUE, rownames=F)
close(accesscon)

3.9 A few notes

sqlFetch and sqlQuery allows as.is = T/F. The meaning of “as.is” can be counterintuitive. On import, all fields are initially assumed to be character strings. During import these are converted to a datatype based on the contents of the column. One might assume that adding “as.is = T” would result in each column being the same type as it was in the original database. Instead, “as.is = T” results in all of the columns being left as character strings. “as.is = F” results in each column being analyzed and changed into an appropriate datatype. “as.is = F” is the default, so you don’t even need to include it!

3.10 stringsAsFactors = F keeps R from converting character strings to factors, which it really likes to do.

4 SQL Server

There are several ways to connect to a SQL Server DB. The main difference is whether you have SQL Server installed on your local machine. The driver is then provided by SQL Server. If SQL Server is not installed on your local machine, you will need to create a named connection (see end of this file for information on creating a named connection).

4.1 Connect to the SQL Server database

Using odbcDriverConnect(). Specify driver, server, and database or create a named connection. Here are the three different connection types.

#create a connection to a SQL Server DB on the local machine
  sqlcon <- odbcDriverConnect("driver=SQL Server Native Client 10.0; server=INPSCPN020011\\SQLEXPRESS; database=ITIS; trusted_connection=yes;")
#create a connection to a SQL Server DB on a server - this will only work if I am connected to the server
  sqlcon2 <- odbcDriverConnect("driver=SQL Server Native Client 10.0; server=INPSCPNMS01\\SQLEXPRESS; database=Demo; trusted_connection=yes;")
#create a connection using a named connection (see end of this file for information on creating a named connection) - this will only work if I am connected to the server
  sqlcon3 <- odbcConnect("MasterPlantDB_INPSCPN020019")

#review the connection
sqlcon

4.6 Use a SQL query to retrieve data from multiple tables

Using sqlQuery().

sqlcon <- odbcDriverConnect("driver=SQL Server Native Client 10.0; server=INPSCPN020011\\SQLEXPRESS; database=ITIS; trusted_connection=yes;")
  output <- sqlQuery(sqlcon, "SELECT Table1.Column, Table2.Column, FROM Table1 INNER JOIN Table2 ON Table1.ID = Table2.ID;")
close(sqlcon)

output
## [1] "42000 156 [Microsoft][SQL Server Native Client 10.0][SQL Server]Incorrect syntax near the keyword 'Column'."                          
## [2] "[RODBC] ERROR: Could not SQLExecDirect 'SELECT Table1.Column, Table2.Column, FROM Table1 INNER JOIN Table2 ON Table1.ID = Table2.ID;'"

5 File Geodatabase

5.1 rgdal package

The rgdal package provides the tools to access data in file geodatabases using a dsn connection.

library(rgdal)

5.2 Set the geodatabase location

  dsn <- "C:\\NAZRUG\\USA.gdb"

ogrListLayers(dsn)

6 Connecting to Microsoft Access 32-bit from R 64-bit

(without an odbc named connection)

Example of getting 32-bit Access data into 64-bit R that you can write into a script so that you don’t need to do the steps manually. You do need to have 32-bit R available on your machine for this to run, and this script assumes a default location for the 32 bit R, so adjust as needed. The first code part goes into your main script, the second code part is the entire contents of a little R script file that you create and is called (sourced) from the main script, this combination extracts and saves and then loads the data from the access database without having to switch between R versions.

This code chunk goes in the main script that will be execulted using 64-bit R

## Lots of script above here
## set the 32-bit script location
  pathIn32BitRScript <- "C:/NAZRUG/GetAccessDbTables.R"

## run the 32 bit script
  system(paste0(Sys.getenv("R_HOME"), "/bin/i386/Rscript.exe ",pathIn32BitRScript))

## Set the path for loading the rda files created from the little script
  pathOutUpAccdb <- "C/NAZRUG/"

## load the tables just created from that script
  load(paste0(pathOutUpAccdb,"customers.rda"))
  load(paste0(pathOutUpAccdb,"vehicles.rda"))

## Processing steps below here

The script below is saved as GetAccessTables.R and is called (sourced) by the file above.

library(RODBC)
#set the database path
  accessdb <- "C:\\NAZRUG\\MikeGarage.accdb"

#connect to the database
  accesscon <- odbcConnectAccess2007(accessdb)
  
#fetch the tables from the database. Modify the as-is and string settings as desired
  customers <- sqlFetch (accesscon,"Customers",as.is=FALSE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  vehicles <- sqlFetch(accesscon,"Vehicles",as.is=FALSE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

#save the tables
  save(customers, file = "C\\NAZRUG\\customers.rda")
  save(vehicles, file = "C:\\NAZRUG\\vehicles.rda")

#close the connection to the db
  close(accesscon)

7 Creating a named ODBC connection to a SQL Server DB

I am not clear on exactly when this is necessary, but we have used this successfully when we do not have SQL Server installed on a machine and want to access data in a SQL Server DB.

This applies to 32-bit.

Select Start, search for and run “odbcad32.exe”.

Select Add.

Select SQL Server Native Client 10.0 for SQL Server 2008, or SQL Server Native Client 11.0 for SQL Server 2014, and then select Finished.

Fill in a name (this is what you will call it by from R).
Give the connection a description.
Point to the SQL Server you wish to use.

Leave these as the default unless you need to change them.

Select your database from the drop down for Change the default database to:.

Leave these as the default unless you need to change them and select Finish.

A result window will pop up showing you the parameters of the connection.

This connection will now appear in the ODBC Data Source Administrator.

Select OK.
